commit_message:
Rework the state documentation

Make the state documentation easier to understand, more
clear, and better stated than what existed before this
commit so it is easier for users to read, use and
interpret.

Change-Id: I0285bfe332c6e968626719f14049a9533d066d86

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-18 17:58:00.000000000', 'message': 'Keystone LDAP domain configuration

Provides keystone-ldap-domain element which does the following:

1. Installs python-ldap module into Keystone virtual environment

2. Generates domain specific configuration file
/etc/keystone/domains/ldap.conf. Settings for the specific LDAP server
are expected to be set via "keystone_ldap" field of ExtraConfig heat
parameter (which is in turn set from OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG env variable
in devtest script).

3. Creates /etc/keystone/domains/ldap.crt file which contans CA
certificates needed to connect to LDAP server. File content is expected
to be passed in as "keystone_ldap_cacertfile" field of
$OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG environment variable.

Configuration settings intended to turn on domain secific configuration
are supposed to be passed via passthrough feature (i.e. injected into
/etc/keystone/keystone.conf file by setting "keystone" field of
$OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG environment variable). In particular,
domain_specific_drivers_enabled option in "identity" section must be set
to True.

Change-Id: I627766c7b2948bd4c4955772e46b5b3e41779248
'}, {'created': '2014-07-22 22:15:37.000000000', 'message': 'Keystone LDAP domain configuration

commit_message:
Keystone LDAP domain configuration

Generate domain specific configuration file
/etc/keystone/domains/keystone.ldap.conf. Please refer to keystone
element README.md file for configuration example.

Change-Id: I627766c7b2948bd4c4955772e46b5b3e41779248

commit_message:
Fix IPC driver on OS X

OS X does not support timeout on semaphore, so the tests block for ever.
Add a test to check that if we support or not that feature.

Change-Id: I1a6bec0d40a5166d5ea9643b5fca128b46b2ec02

commit_message:
Make keystone_pki less keystone specific

We need to create ssl certs for services other than Keystone. Renaming
keystone_pki to ssl_pki, and making the routines less keystone specific
so we can create certs for other services.

Also creating generate_ssl_cert command which can generate ssl
certificates for multiple services using a single CA.

Change-Id: I4d65cceee9e15ce0ca8ef309127a587135355810

commit_message:
Fix NetAppDirectCmodeNfsDriver._find_shares()

If more than one NFS share is defined, all volumes are allocated on the
same NFS share until it is not eligible anymore. Then a second NFS share
is filled. The code is supposed to split volumes between the different
NFS shares, not fill them one by one.

It is a bug in _find_shares(). If at least one NFS share is eligible,
the "size" parameter (size of the requested volume in gigabytes) is
replaced with the total size in bytes of the share. Because of that,
_find_shares() cannot find more one eligible NFS share.

_find_shares() sorts eligible volumes by available size. Because of this
bug, all volumes are allocated in the same NFS share, instead of being
splitted on different NFS shares.

Co-author: "Florent Flament" <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: I70e33746b99306eb246096ee02c538910d2a370b

commit_message:
Add version-properties builder to macros.yaml

The source version-properties is used by several jobs, instead
of defining a shell block everywhere better to have it into
macros.yaml for better reuse.
This new builder runs version-properties.sh and sources the
file created with the inject builder.

Change-Id: I2e13fd0f982ee8f426a714e25d1f52593d0ad5ba

Is there any evidence that this syntax is actually preferred or part of the standards, as the commit message suggests?'}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2014-09-07 13:29:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Roger - I am not sure if this is preferred, but form what I have glanced over the only one that is not documented this way is Neutron, all the others, glance, nova, swift, heat, cinder, ceilometer and trove all use the convention with a "=" like the proposed change.

It is your Documentation people's call.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-09-07 14:22:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The CLI reference has no equal signs:

http://docs.openstack.org/cli-reference/content/keystoneclient_commands.html

Also, equal signs have been removed since Icehouse at least here:

http://docs.openstack.org/icehouse/install-guide/install/apt/content/keystone-users.html

http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/install-guide/install/apt/content/keystone-users.html

I remain unconvinced that equal signs are standard (but won't object if they are)."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-09-07 16:46:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

Let's discuss on the mailing list first. Marking with -2 until we reached a consensus which direction to take.

Thanks for the patch and raising this!"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-09-08 20:06:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

As discussed on the mailing list, we will go with "--option ARGUMENT" without the equal sign.

Could you abandon this patch, please? Patches to change the other places are welcome as well!'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-22 16:44:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-10-03 07:12:18.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Unfortunately, based on my reading, it seems the community has gone with the alternate syntax. Your work is very much appreciated, but to keep the review system clean, we should close this patch.'}]

commit_message:
Change syntax for Install guide

This change adds syntax to include "=" between the parameter name
and the value to conform to the standards that are used within the
rest of the Install Guide.

Added the syntax in 2a, 2b, 2c, 2d.

Change-Id: I04c221197eb43b61c88dcd3b38486aa87e476294
Closes-Bug: #1366473

The change is technically fine. But it is a change that happened for Icehouse, so is only correct for Icehouse and newer.

Anne, which versions does the HA guide cover? Do we need to mention this somehow?'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-09-09 18:15:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Just discussed on IRC: The guide covers both Havana and Icehouse. Could you update the information so that it's correct for Havana as well, please?"}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-09-09 19:20:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

For very operations-oriented deliverables like the HA Guide, Security Guide, and Ops Guide, it's typically an older target because the audience prefers stability. 

We try to have writers write these guides for guidance and not super release-specific. So ideally you'd write about both havana and icehouse, noting what's unique for each.

I'll include this on the docs wiki pages as well, but these are the current state to my knowledge:
Ops Guide: Icehouse target, revised specifically to target that release
Sec Guide: written prior to Havana release
HA Guide: updated last at Havana timeframe, still needs updates"}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:13:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-20 05:29:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-10-03 07:09:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Closing, because the repository changed under us! Please propose this change to the new ha-guide repository instead :)'}]

commit_message:
Add document for EMC VMAX driver

The EMC VMAX driver in Juno is an enhancement from the EMC SMI-S
driver in Icehouse. In Juno, this driver only supports VMAX and
no longer supports VNX. This patch reflects this change in the driver.

Change-Id: I4c91e292b6b29774a3860289a1b83d81551e8528

commit_message:
Fix common_translation_update

Use "git rm -f" to force removal. We might have files that were changed by
the previous steps and then "git rm" will fail with:
$ git rm heat/locale/fr/LC_MESSAGES/heat-log-warning.po
error: 'heat/locale/fr/LC_MESSAGES/heat-log-warning.po' has changes
 staged in the index
| (use --cached to keep the file, or -f to force removal)

This change is needed to fix propose_translation_update.sh for a few
repositories including heat.

Change-Id: Ia5887a0442a25d6bd66351f266cb392cb46ca4d5

commit_message:
Remove untranslated PO files

The proposal bot only imports file that are at least 75 % translated.
Remove any PO file that is untranslated or has less than 75 % of
translations.
Note this removes actually all files.

See https://www.transifex.com/projects/p/trove/ for details as well

Checked number of translated entries with:

for i in `find . -name *.po `; do msgfmt --statistics -v $i; done

Whenever a file is again translated sufficiently, the proposal bot will
propose a new patch - thus we do not lose any translations.

Change-Id: I1f5d947822cd4f60a3e719f8727f758f651896fd

commit_message:
autohelp: Remove trailing spaces from help strings

Some help strings have a trailing space that make our tests fail. These
spaces should be removed from the help strings in the projects, but it
takes time and we often end up editing manually.

Help strings from the oslo incubator might already have been fixed but
not yet imported in the projects, so no proper solution exists in this
case.

Change-Id: I606f46b23a4c5a5114bb5577273657fdf4fa5295

(1 comment)

What would be the actual gain from having the classes inherit from the formatters? Maybe it would be even an option to have the classes not inherit from the formatters, and have the formatters as completely separated entities whose only purpose is to print the representation of their respective objects.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:14:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

It helps specifically with Containers due to the Typed Containers having different printing methods. It makes it seamless/transparent at a higher level, so no one has to figure out which formatter to use when writing their own code.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:29:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Also, if the classes don't inherit from the Formatters, we're back to square one with regard to "what does str(my_container) return?" We could force people to use the formatters at the time they want to print, but is the string representation of the class just a random object id? I *much* prefer this method.'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2014-09-08 07:19:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Your explanation makes sense; Lets just separate those imports and it's a +1 from me."}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-09-08 19:43:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Yeah, the reasons I ended up doing it that way is because:

A) Hacking/pep8 accepts it as valid, so I am not sure if it needs to be changed?

B) "from barbicanclient.barbican_cli.containers import CertificateContainerFormatter" is too long for one line, and I honestly don't know how I'd do that import without using parentheses anyway.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-09-08 20:08:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-08 20:43:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

I think this is logically ready and am satisfied with the solution. But after giving it a good thought: for semantics, now that the formatters are more part of the actual classes more than a cli-only utility; can you move the formatter code outside the cli folder?

I think having the formatter classes alongside, in the same file as their respective entities is a better choice than having them in the cli part; Since the __str__ usage will not only be used in the cli, but also the library itself.'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2014-09-09 07:11:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

On the other hand, since the formatters are now part of the entities, you could refactor the code such that you no longer need to pass the entity itself to _get_formatted_*. This is because now the formatter, being a mixin with the entity, has access to the state of the internal variables of it and can freely access them.'}, {'account_id': 7262, 'date': '2014-09-10 18:25:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Minor comments. Not sure how my comments would be in the grand scheme of the changes Juan is talking about, but I thought I would add them anyhow.'}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-09-10 18:39:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)

Juan, I actually agree with you as well, and I think I will make this change and we'll see how it looks. commit_message:
Change object __str__() to use pretty formatting

Use the EntityFormatter framework to generate str() for objects,
and render them using prettytable. Replaces the old manual __str__()
method.

Change-Id: Icf6f37f4a677595f3aaa8d305c2c8cd4676e72fa

subject: Use tox for bashate testing
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-30 14:31:02.000000000', 'message': 'Use tox for bashate testing

Create a tox.ini file to install bashate into a virtualenv for running

commit_message:
Use tox for bashate testing

Create a tox.ini file to install bashate into a virtualenv for running
tests. It can be run with a command such as "tox -v -ebashate". The find
command being used is equivalent to the default list of files discovered
by bashate plus the exclusion of the .tox/ directory. Also add the .tox/
directory to the .gitignore file.

Conflicts:
	.gitignore

Change-Id: I94cab4e4a9118d62edfce29ead1f1e2a5f48e529
(cherry picked from commit 0c256abd766265b8fdb11d354be7115c05bcaeb5)

commit_message:
Adds missing exception handling in resize and rebuild servers API

Adds handling of NoValidHost and AutoDiskConfigDisabledByImage in
resize and rebuild of the V3 servers API. This has already been
fixed in the V2 API.

Change-Id: I5a5519f87bb220d6821e959f36dc5b36ffe9cc2d

commit_message:
Don't parse config file if it doesn't exist

This commit adds a check before we parse the config file to see if the
config file actually exists. If it doesn't we shouldn't try to parse
it. There is still an issue with one scenario test that uses
testscenarios but it doesn't result in an error code being raised by a
test-list so that can be tracked down separately.

Change-Id: Iac31f2edcfbccf8c06d73c6ca01e30c8319c0485
Closes-Bug: #1369118

The 'cinder manage' command argumenst are kind of a disaster.
The positionals are <host> <id> where <id> is undefined/free form
K/V pairs.  On top of it we then have --source-name and --source-id
optional arguments available.  There absolutely no way to tell from
the help what one should be entering here without referring to the
code, and even then it's not quite clear how the options work and

where both are strings.  Remove --source-name and --source-id
and consolidate those options with --id-type.

id-type will allow a user to specify the type of identifier
(source-name, source-id, or whatever), but defaults to
source-name which is most commonly used currently.

commit_message:
Simplify cinder manage command args

The 'cinder manage' command argumenst are kind of a disaster.
The positionals are <host> <id> where <id> is undefined/free form
K/V pairs.  On top of it we then have --source-name and --source-id
optional arguments available.  There absolutely no way to tell from
the help what one should be entering here without referring to the
code, and even then it's not quite clear how the options work and
which one will be used.

To clean this up, change the positionals to <host> <identifier>
where both are strings.  Remove --source-name and --source-id
and consolidate those options with --id-type.

id-type will allow a user to specify the type of identifier
(source-name, source-id, or whatever), but defaults to
source-name which is most commonly used currently.

* NOTE *
Ideally we'd just do away with the designator source-name/source-id
altogether and just have an <identifier> positional arg.  Each driver
would then be responsible for figuring out what was passed an how to
deal with it.  This however requires changes in all of the drivers and
broader changes on the Cinder side which I don't think are warranted
during RC.

During Kilo we should clean all of this up, but for now at least the
syntax is somewhat ready for human consumption and a bit easier than
what we introduced.

Change-Id: I07696648ae647f17ab9180cd87b25f8cb888f5d6
Closes-Bug: 1376311

[{'created': '2014-10-01 14:41:54.000000000', 'message': 'Remove duplicated index instances_host_deleted_idx

Index instances_host_deleted_idx covers the host and deleted columns on
the instances table. However, index instances_host_deleted_cleaned_idx
is a superset and covers the host, deleted and cleaned columns. Both
MySQL and PostgreSQL can use instances_host_deleted_cleaned_idx even
if only the host and deleted are in the where statement.

instances_host_deleted_idx is superfluous and just adds extra overhead
to inserts and updates on the instances table.
or updates.

Change-Id: I397c7f1ba9ab95a99f13c9ec6e838ae63987870b
'}, {'created': '2014-10-01 16:08:39.000000000', 'message': "Remove indexes that are prefix subsets of other indexes

Both MySQL and PostgreSQL can efficiently optimize queries using
indexes that use the prefix columns of the index. This means that
an index that covers columns (a, b, c) can be used to optimize
a query with the statement 'WHERE a = 1 and b = 9'.

Nova has indexes which are a prefix subset of other indexes. The
database servers can use the suffix superset indexes and the prefix
subset indexes just add extra overhead to inserts and updates.

instances_host_deleted_idx (host, deleted) is a prefix subset of
instances_host_deleted_cleaned_idx (host, deleted, cleaned)

iscsi_targets_host_idx (host) is a prefix subset of
iscsi_targets_host_volume_id_deleted_idx (host, volume_id, deleted)

Change-Id: I397c7f1ba9ab95a99f13c9ec6e838ae63987870b
"}]
commit_message:
Remove indexes that are prefix subsets of other indexes

Both MySQL and PostgreSQL can efficiently optimize queries using
indexes that use the prefix columns of the index. This means that
an index that covers columns (a, b, c) can be used to optimize
a query with the statement 'WHERE a = 1 and b = 9'.

Nova has indexes which are a prefix subset of other indexes. The
database servers can use the suffix superset indexes and the prefix
subset indexes just add extra overhead to inserts and updates.

instances_host_deleted_idx (host, deleted) is a prefix subset of
instances_host_deleted_cleaned_idx (host, deleted, cleaned)

iscsi_targets_host_idx (host) is a prefix subset of
iscsi_targets_host_volume_id_deleted_idx (host, volume_id, deleted)

Change-Id: I397c7f1ba9ab95a99f13c9ec6e838ae63987870b

Add config file for rally-designate job

Currently this job may be triggered by 'check experimental' (when all
necessary patches are merged in openstack/infra)

Change-Id: Ia7004ec968350648bc32d72af7a316b897853da7

commit_message:
Hard delete backup stack after successful update.

After successful update of a stack, the backup stack and it's associated
template, resources and events should be permanently deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1332300

Change-Id: I3a462690b5f6bfadfbcf16eeb6bdec7c5ece2e83

commit_message:
Add current_size attribute for OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup

User can use this output attribute to get the current size
of AutoscalingResourceGroup.

Change-Id: I6756e85aa3435a822aa72139cac7aabd8254079d

commit_message:
ilo* drivers to use only ilo credentials

Currently IloVirtualMediaIscsiDriver and IloVirtualMediaAgentDriver
and pxe_ilo driver uses ipmitool for console and management interfaces.
This imposes user/operator to specify ipmi credentials along with ilo
credentials (which are same) during creation of node.

This fix proposes to update the ipmi credentials on the fly by inheriting
IPMI console and Management Interface.

Change-Id: I81c1311b05bd00bb8245ceb71a140f6bdd2e7daa
Closes-bug:#1367182

commit_message:
Provide support status info for some resources

Define the support_status attribute for resources added during the
icehouse and juno cycles. The `version` provided is the tag of the
stable release.

Implements: blueprint heat-templates

rebased on top of the periodic task, and updated the commit message accordingly.

why? I think we have two scenarios for the patch order:
- change mapping, then add periodic task
==> an upgrade between these is unrecoverable (until the second patch is applied)
- add periodic task, then change mapping
==> an upgrade between these could yield a lot of unnecessary rebalancing

so I think #2 is better'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-29 22:56:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 15.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-29 23:23:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: -Code-Review

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-04 00:52:21.000000000', 'message': 'Fix hash ring stability

Nejc Saje reported on the openstack-dev list that our hash ring
was not stable as hosts were added or removed. This is a significant
issue since the hash ring is meant to minimise the impact of adding
or removing conductors to only approximately the change in capacity.

IMPORTANT: When this patch is added to a running Ironic environment it
will cause ring calculations to change. This will cause all existing
node -> conductor mappings to be invalid, and unless a rebalance is
triggered immediately, that will cause existing deployed nodes to be
unable to reboot (if using a netbooting driver like pxe_ipmi).

Change-Id: Iad3c9f6b460e9162ca91d5719e42f7950f2f18df
UpgradeImpact: See above.

'}, {'created': '2014-09-28 01:36:08.000000000', 'message': 'Fix hash ring stability

Nejc Saje reported on the openstack-dev list that our hash ring
was not stable as hosts were added or removed. This is a significant
issue since the hash ring is meant to minimise the impact of adding
or removing conductors to only approximately the change in capacity.

IMPORTANT: When this patch is added to a running Ironic environment it
will cause ring calculations to change. This will cause all existing
node -> conductor mappings to be invalid, and unless a rebalance is
triggered immediately, that will cause existing deployed nodes to be
unable to reboot (if using a netbooting driver like pxe_ipmi).

The meaning of the hash_partition_exponent configuration setting has
had to be changed - if we define the total number of partitions of the
ring via it then adding a host simultaneously removes some partitions
of each existing host as well as adding new partitions from the new
host - this results in more perturbation. Instead we use it to define
the number of partitions per host. Existing deployments will continue
to work, but may be able to reduce some CPU overhead by shrinking
their setting.

Change-Id: Iad3c9f6b460e9162ca91d5719e42f7950f2f18df
Closes-Bug: #1365334
DocImpact: See above.
UpgradeImpact: See above.

commit_message:
Make hash ring mapping be more consistent

Nejc Saje reported on the openstack-dev list that our hash ring was not
stable as hosts were added or removed. This is a significant issue since
the hash ring is meant to minimize the impact of adding or removing
conductors to only approximately the change in capacity.

IMPORTANT: When this patch is added to a running Ironic environment it
will cause ring calculations to change. This will cause most existing
node -> conductor mappings to be invalid, which will cause existing
deployed nodes to be unable to reboot (if using a netbooting driver like
pxe_ipmi). The cluster will self-correct over time as the periodic task
_sync_hash_ring() rebuilds PXE environments.

NOTE: The meaning of the hash_partition_exponent configuration setting
had to be changed - if we define the total number of partitions of the
ring via it then adding a host simultaneously removes some partitions of
each existing host as well as adding new partitions from the new host -
this results in more perturbation. Instead we use it to define the
number of partitions per host. Existing deployments will continue to
work, but may be able to reduce some CPU overhead by shrinking their
setting.

Change-Id: Iad3c9f6b460e9162ca91d5719e42f7950f2f18df
Closes-Bug: #1365334
DocImpact: See above.
UpgradeImpact: See above.

commit_message:
Remove cinder-keystone-setup script

This is a legacy script from the tools/openstack days, so we don't
need it now as that script no longer exists.

Change-Id: Iddcd76739447e65fcbf4f4bac517cf4fd919fac9

image schema and which are not a base image property. Proposed fix skips
every non-base property when building a json patch, that is used to
update image properties through glance API.

commit_message:
Skip non-base properties in patch method

It's currently impossible to update properties which are defined in
image schema and which are not a base image property. Proposed fix skips
every non-base property when building a json patch, that is used to
update image properties through glance API.

Change-Id: I3b35cef379fcf437715e2966f9a0d25c1b4e4016
Closes-Bug: #1371559

Hi Christian,

I really like your idea. Although I found a bug that made the rebalance not working as expected. Basically, when there were n partitions available in a new tier, you added these partitions to every tier level (device, node, zone, region), but didn't decrease the available partitions accordingly when reassigning a partition.

Also I removed the 1% partitions reassigned when no partitions were wanted on other tiers, because it suffered the same issue than available partitions, but I didn't manage to find a solution to get the expected behavior. Besides, I didn't really understand the benefit of adding these 1%.

Please have a look at the patch I uploaded, as I believe that it fixes this issue. Rebalancing with new region looks very good now.

--- Here's my results ---

With this new patch, when add a new node to a new region with 10 nodes in initial region

Partitions count for new device: 61

Total partitions moved: 66 (3.22265625%)

With former patch (same scenario)

Partitions count for new device: 61

Total partitions moved: 444 (21.6796875%)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-20 04:23:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

Florent, thanks for the update, nice catch!

My idea to allow 1% of the partitions to move freely was to make sure that tiers at risk can shift partitions, even when parts_wanted is 0 for all devices. Looks like this is not needed at all, and I didn't found a problem with this yet.

I found a small issue because self.available_parts_for_tier[tier] might not be set yet; thus I changed the code to initialize all tiers on the first call.

Florent, I just checked what happens when I add two new regions at the same time. I used the following script:

 swift-ring-builder test.builder create 11 3 0

 for i in `seq 1 9`; do
     swift-ring-builder test.builder add r1z0-127.0.0.$i:6000/sda1 100
 done
 swift-ring-builder test.builder rebalance

 swift-ring-builder test.builder add r2z0-127.0.0.10:6000/sdb1 50
 swift-ring-builder test.builder add r3z0-127.0.0.11:6000/sdb1 50
 swift-ring-builder test.builder rebalance

The result is:

 Reassigned 630 (30.76%) partitions. Balance is now 0.26.

Region 2+3 are 1/10th of the total weight. There are 3 * 2048 partitions = 6144 -> 10% is 615 partitions, and 630 moved. The behavior looks stable for larger number of devices too.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-14 20:54:27.000000000', 'message': 'Limit partition movement when rebalancing

When adding new regions or zones to an existing, already balanced ring
it is very likely that a lot of partitions will be gathered for
reassigning, even when there is not enough space in the new region or
zone. This will create a lot of unnecessary replication traffic in the
backend network.

This patch limits the number of partitions that are choosen to reassign
by checking for devices on other tiers that are asking for more
partitions. 10% of the partitions are allowed to move, even when no
devices on other tiers ask for more partitions.

Failed devices are not considered when applying the limit.

Change-Id: I6178452e47492da4677a8ffe4fb24917b5968cd9
Closes-Bug: 1367826
'}, {'created': '2014-09-15 06:46:27.000000000', 'message': 'Limit partition movement when rebalancing

When adding new regions or zones to an existing, already balanced ring
it is very likely that a lot of partitions will be gathered for
reassigning, even when there is not enough space in the new region or
zone. This will create a lot of unnecessary replication traffic in the
backend network.

The reason behind this is the way partitions are gathered for
reassigning: when a new region or zone is added, the existing
region/zone tiers are allowed to store fewer replicas and all partitions
in this region/zone are selected for reassigning. However, if the new
region/zone has not enough space for all partitions, they will be
reassigned to the existing region/zone.

This patch limits the number of partitions that are choosen to reassign
to a different region/zone by checking for devices on other tiers that
are asking for more partitions. 5% of the partitions are allowed to
move, even when no devices on other tiers ask for more partitions.

Failed devices are not considered when applying the limit.

Change-Id: I6178452e47492da4677a8ffe4fb24917b5968cd9
Closes-Bug: 1367826

'}, {'created': '2014-09-17 18:22:37.000000000', 'message': 'Limit partition movement when adding a new tier

When adding a new tier (region, zone, node, device) to an existing,
already balanced ring all existing partitions in the existing tiers of
the same level are gathered for reassigning, even when there is
not enough space in the new tier. This will create a lot of unnecessary
replication traffic in the backend network.

For example, when only one region exists in the ring and a new region is
added, all existing parts are selected, even when the new region has a
total weight of 0. Same for one zones, nodes and devices.

This patch limits the number of partitions that are choosen to reassign
by checking for devices on other tiers that are asking for more
partitions. 10% of the partitions are allowed to move, even when no
devices on other tiers ask for more partitions.

Failed devices are not considered when applying the limit.

Also-By: Florent Flament <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: I6178452e47492da4677a8ffe4fb24917b5968cd9
Closes-Bug: 1367826

commit_message:
Limit partition movement when adding a new tier

When adding a new tier (region, zone, node, device) to an existing,
already balanced ring all existing partitions in the existing tiers of
the same level are gathered for reassigning, even when there is
not enough space in the new tier. This will create a lot of unnecessary
replication traffic in the backend network.

For example, when only one region exists in the ring and a new region is
added, all existing parts are selected to reassign, even when the new
region has a total weight of 0. Same for zones, nodes and devices.

This patch limits the number of partitions that are choosen to reassign
by checking for devices on other tiers that are asking for more
partitions.

Failed devices are not considered when applying the limit.

Co-Authored By: Florent Flament <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: I6178452e47492da4677a8ffe4fb24917b5968cd9
Closes-Bug: 1367826

The validation here needs to happen only in the account and container servers, not in the brokers.

With validation in the brokers, you can get two container DBs that each have N metadata items, where N is the maximum allowed, but only have N-1 in common. When replication tries to merge them, it'll call the broker's update_metadata() method, and that will fail with an exception, leaving the DBs unchanged. Then next replication pass, it'll happen again.

This will make the limit a little more fuzzy thanks to eventual consistency, but lots of things in Swift are like that already."}, {'account_id': 7433, 'date': '2014-10-02 20:22:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 7433, 'date': '2014-10-02 21:30:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 7433, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:03:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:15:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 7433, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:38:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:39:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:44:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:45:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-10-02 22:52:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 23:31:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix metadata overall limits bug

Currently metadata limits are checked on a per request basis. If
multiple requests are sent within the per request limits, it is
possible to exceed the overall limits.  This patch adds an overall
metadata check to ensure that multiple requests to add metadata to
an account/container will check overall limits before adding
the additional metadata.

Change-Id: Ib9401a4ee05a9cb737939541bd9b84e8dc239c70
Closes-Bug: 1365350

commit_message:
HOT for IIS with Drupal

It deploys a new Drupal 7 web site on a server with IIS
and PHP 5.4 configured. Web site uses a local database on
SQL Server 2008 R2 SP2 Express

Required tools are downloaded from the internet using
official links. SHA1 hashes are computed for the downloaded files
and compared with the expected hashes to ensure file integrity.

The unit tests for the user data scripts are written using
Pester 3.0

Change-Id: Ia9c12db0a92fc4f39be9056c67471eb8c136a86a
Partially-Implements: blueprint windows-instances

Set known_stores value in glance config file

known_stores should be set if we are using non-default store for glance

Closes-bug: #1374366

commit_message:
updated hacking rules

1) Added comment for H231, which we were already enforcing. H231
is for Python 3.x compatible except statements.

2) Added check for H201, which we were enforcing in reviews
but waiting on hacking checks to be updated. H201 is for bare
except statements, and the update in upstream hacking is to
support the "  # noqa" flag on it.

The H201 check catches some existing bare excepts that are fixed.

Change-Id: I68638aa9ea925ef62f9035a426548c2c804911a8

commit_message:
use released library versions by default

This patch provides a new path for installing libraries in devstack so
that it's possible to either test with upstream released libraries, or
with git versions of individual libraries.

Libraries are added by name to 3 associative arrays GITREPO,
GITBRANCH, GITDIR. When we get to the library install phase we inspect
LIBS_FROM_GIT and look for libraries by name (i.e. "oslo.config") and
if they exist we'll clone and install those libraries from
git. Otherwise we won't, and just let pip pull them as dependencies
when it needs them.

This patch provides the conversion of the oslo libraries, including
pbr.

Devstack-gate jobs for these libraries will need to change to support
actually forward testing their content.

cleaned for requests in unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1353506

[{'created': '2014-10-02 21:26:01.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ring-builder crash.

If you adjust the replica count after adding devices but before the
first rebalance, the ring builder would crash.

To reproduce:

    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder create 8 3 1
    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder add r1z1-10.1.1.1:6000/sda1 1
    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder set_replicas 5
    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder rebalance

Change-Id: Id91cf8680961ccf6e3db153577e99cad545bee9d
'}]
commit_message:
Fix ring-builder crash.

If you adjust the replica count after adding devices but before the
first rebalance, the ring builder would crash.

To reproduce:

    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder create 8 3 1
    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder add r1z1-10.1.1.1:6000/sda1 1
    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder set_replicas 5
    $ swift-ring-builder crashy.builder rebalance

Change-Id: Id91cf8680961ccf6e3db153577e99cad545bee9d

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-01 22:53:37.000000000', 'message': "Destroy orig VM during resize if triggered by user

Patch I7598afbf0dc3c527471af34224003d28e64daaff introduces a
Minesweeper failure, due to the fact that it doesn't distinguishes
between destroy operation triggered by the user and by the revert
resize.

This patch fixes the issue by checking the task state. If the task
state is revert_resize, the original VM doesn't get deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1376492

Change-Id: Idb9ac6c1ec5dcea52ce8e028f5cce08da1779321

commit_message:
Destroy orig VM during resize if triggered by user

Patch I7598afbf0dc3c527471af34224003d28e64daaff introduces a
Minesweeper failure, due to the fact that it doesn't distinguish
between destroy operation triggered by the user and by the revert
resize.

This patch fixes the issue by checking the task state. If the task
state is revert_resize, the original VM doesn't get deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1376492

Change-Id: Idb9ac6c1ec5dcea52ce8e028f5cce08da1779321

[{'created': '2014-09-29 11:48:40.000000000', 'message': "test_v3_token_id correctly hash token

The test_v3_token_id test was calculating the token hash by
parsing the response JSON and generating a new JSON document.
This isn't guaranteed to work because a Python dict can have its
fields in any order[1], so the new JSON document may not match the
response JSON and you'd get a different hash. The correct way to
generate a token hash is to use the response as is.

[1] http://docs.python.org/2/library/stdtypes.html#dict.items

Change-Id: I1a79c252916c4459fdc75a6e022d72c0c14582ef
(cherry picked from commit 5257f65e57b4387fe93a2fb30983f2e1d856e609)
"}]
commit_message:
test_v3_token_id correctly hash token

The test_v3_token_id test was calculating the token hash by
parsing the response JSON and generating a new JSON document.
This isn't guaranteed to work because a Python dict can have its
fields in any order[1], so the new JSON document may not match the
response JSON and you'd get a different hash. The correct way to
generate a token hash is to use the response as is.

[1] http://docs.python.org/2/library/stdtypes.html#dict.items

Change-Id: I1a79c252916c4459fdc75a6e022d72c0c14582ef
(cherry picked from commit 5257f65e57b4387fe93a2fb30983f2e1d856e609)

commit_message:
Catch permission denied exception when update host

When an existing non-openstack instance in the compute node contains
disk file which can not be accessed by nova non-root user, resources can
not be updated successfully when periodic task is running. Also the
nova-compute service could not be restared again. We should catch such
exception.

Change-Id: I75195417e123f135252470cf1322843830556b0a
Closes-Bug: 1322467
(cherry picked from commit ebecfd496ec8aaef07a401d3c90e2e5da406d16f)

commit_message:
Allow forms to disable autofill in all browsers

New variable added to form to specify whether it should autofill or
not. This updates the modal forms autocomplete attribute. Hidden
fields are required because Chromium v34+ based browsers ignore the
autocomplete=off form attribute, so the hidden fields catch autofill
data. Any form without self.no_autocomplete = True will just act
like before.

Conflicts:
	horizon/templates/horizon/common/_modal_form.html
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/users/forms.py

Change-Id: Ibb1722023eea8f57312e1133939d1f75cd909467
Closes-Bug: 1352459
(cherry picked from commit e79af0ac1e273db86f0034898cb05720df34aa35)

commit_message:
Support for languagepack build command

This patch is related to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125731/

This change allows an end user to pass in a languagepack
metadata file while building a custom languagepack. The
final glance image created will be tagged with this data.

Change-Id: I7cd6ad2db95940ed11be437327e0c6e0b0e6f644

commit_message:
Ensure sbin is in PATH.

Some distros (Debian) don't have sbin in PATH for non-root users.

Nova (and possibly other services) assumes that it can invoke "sysctl"
without sudo.

Change-Id: Iced21fc1378af309fb49688f9b63f2cd8383e304
Closes-Bug: #1300800

commit_message:
Fix glance V2 incorrectly implements JSON Patch'add'

According to the RFC for JSON Patch
http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6902#section-4.1
the 'add' operation, in the event that the property being
added already exists, should replace the existing value. For backward
compatibility We've fix it only for the latest content type.

Change-Id: Ia4be8b384f8b7f193f139f2206ceea25786b5cc3
Closes-bug: 1250158
DocImpact
Partial-bug: #1277104

commit_message:
Fix zuul_swift_upload to use old MAGIC_MIME const

The magic bindings updated to not prefix their constants with
MAGIC. Centos has an old version so we need to use the old constant
names (which are backwards compatible).

I've tested this on centos6 and ubuntu 12.04

Change-Id: Ic64c7395323e7583b37cf624d062cc3f40c89893

[{'created': '2014-10-02 17:11:47.000000000', 'message': "Refuse invalid qcow2 backing files

Don't allow qcow2 files that are pointing to backing files outside of:

volume-<id>
volume-<id>.<snap-id>
volume-<id>.tmp-snap-<snap-id>

(optionally prefixed with /mnt/path)

Closes-Bug: #1350504

Change-Id: Ic89cffc93940b7b119cfcde3362f304c9f2875df
"}]
commit_message:
Refuse invalid qcow2 backing files

Don't allow qcow2 files that are pointing to backing files outside of:

volume-<id>
volume-<id>.<snap-id>
volume-<id>.tmp-snap-<snap-id>

(optionally prefixed with /mnt/path)

Closes-Bug: #1350504

Change-Id: Ic89cffc93940b7b119cfcde3362f304c9f2875df

commit_message:
ZFSSA iSCSI vol create fails with vol type option

Vol create with volume-type option is not working since
volume_backend_name contains the class name as
predefined string. No matter what was specified in cinder.conf
as volume_backend_name, volume creation failed.
Multi-backend option and using extra specs to create custom volumes
won't work.
The fix is to look whether volume_backend_name is part of the
configuration or falls into the class name in case there is
no backend name.

Change-Id: I1bc501dd4c5689d96c7beb720b64112df1770232
Closes-Bug: 1373621
DocImpact

  are not compatible with DB2. In DB2, Boolean columns are created as

commit_message:
Update migration scripts to support DB2

Three of the migration scripts are causing failures with DB2.

- DB2 doesn't support nullable column in primary key

- Hard coded SQL statements which use False/True as Boolean arguments
  are not compatible with DB2. In DB2, Boolean columns are created as
  small integer with a constraint to allow only 0 & 1.

- Hardcoded update rows from other table sql is not compatible with DB2

- Foreign key constraints require additional handling

Co-authored-by: Rahul Priyadarshi <rahul.priyadarshi@in.ibm.com>
Change-Id: I82e2d1c522b81fed90a1e5cc6f2321f80797cf7b
Closes-Bug: #1328019

LGTM !'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2014-09-29 09:19:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Jumping from the perfect 50%-50% balance to the at least one/ server is a big jump. On single node system without playing with service restarts ha-proxy can do the 50%-50% (single process) with a very high chance of success (always?).

With more complex proxy system probably guaranteeing the 50%-50% perfect balance is not a realistic requirement. 

Can you `expect` at least 25% per node and add extra numbers to the exception(or LOG) about the details when it fails ?'}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2014-09-29 11:36:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

afazekas, have you read Armando's comment (11 september) ?

He said, and I agree, that it's not Tempest job to check the LB (haproxy or other implementations) evenly (or close to evenly) spreads the requests among the servers. What do you think ?

You suggest 25% but it's a bit of a "magic number". Why 25% and not 33% for instance ?'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:04:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@afazekas: what datapoint do you expect to collect if we did that? We could only infer that HA proxy is not round robin requests across; but is this an effect of the backend implementation that by mistake went from RR to another distribution algorithm, or something else happened? In the former case, for example, a functional test is hardly something you would do to protect yourself from regressions (a UT is more appropriate). Bottom line is that you cannot tell reliably, so making the test more complicated and adding artificial thresholds seems unnecessary.

IMO, all we should care here is that Neutron wires the LB correctly and that it can load balance requests across.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:24:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

LGTM, just a nit for using the wrong type of assert then this will have my +2.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-09-29 18:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

As for the py26 story, we don't care about it in tempest I think there is a note about that in the README.

It has been observed that only one of the two HTTP services
responds to requests made to the VIP. This is somewhat rare
and it may be caused by the fact that the number of requests
being sent is not high enough for the ROUNDROBIN algorithm to
equally distribute requests across all the members in the
pool.

Increasing the number of retries makes the test runtime only
slightly longer, but it should give us more confidence that,
if we keep observing the same type of failure, this can be
ruled out.

Closes-bug: 1358857

'}, {'created': '2014-09-11 17:51:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix MismatchError for LB scenario test

Increasing the number of retries makes the test runtime only slightly
longer, but it should give us more confidence that, if we keep observing

that member pools are load balanced at least once. Verifying that the the
number of requests are spread evenly accross is always going to be prone to
transient condition and it is beyond the scope of a scenario test that validates
whether Neutron LBaaS is wiring things correctly.

Closes-bug: 1358857

commit_message:
Fix MismatchError for LB scenario test

It has been observed that at a given iteration only one of the two HTTP
services responds to requests made to the VIP. This is somewhat rare and
it may be caused by the fact that the number of requests being sent is
not high enough for the ROUNDROBIN algorithm to equally distribute requests
across all the members in the pool.

Increasing the number of retries makes the test runtime only slightly
longer, but it should give us more confidence that, if we keep observing
the same type of failure, this can be ruled out.

At the same time, this patch also relaxes the check so that it just verifies
that member pools are load balanced at least once. Verifying that the number
of requests are spread evenly across is always going to be prone to transient
condition and it is beyond the scope of a scenario test that validates whether
Neutron LBaaS is wiring things correctly.

Closes-bug: #1358857

Change-Id: Ibc0aeb092a4643eb151cef8d7d942d9e3d1ed71c

commit_message:
Use shared values for test_security_group_rules

In test_security_group_rules, most created security group rules are
the same. This patch adds shared values and makes these tests use
them for cleanup.

Change-Id: Ie86c33217fc6b065844e31f9b6e37be93322f2cb

There were tests that verified that the PKI token body could be
encrypted with CMS and compared to the token ID in the response.
This test isn't safe because the token body may be different than
the token encrypted with CMS since the order of items in the dict
can change.

The fix is to change the test to decode the PKI token ID and
compare that to the response body JSON instead.

Change-Id: Icc649b96071ff084d5c76f2ea2bcf3ecb08a0351
(cherry picked from commit 83394ba71ba06e9899aaa62f211919075f2a3d91)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix tests comparing tokens

There were tests that verified that the PKI token body could be
encrypted with CMS and compared to the token ID in the response.
This test isn't safe because the token body may be different than
the token encrypted with CMS since the order of items in the dict
can change.

The fix is to change the test to decode the PKI token ID and
compare that to the response body JSON instead.

Change-Id: Icc649b96071ff084d5c76f2ea2bcf3ecb08a0351
(cherry picked from commit 83394ba71ba06e9899aaa62f211919075f2a3d91)

commit_message:
Fix HDFS url description, and other various edits

HDFS url description is wrong as a result of code changes. This was
the major motivation for this CR.

Additional changes

* formatted for 80 characters
* consistent use of '.' at the end of bullets
* added mention of Spark
* adding '.sahara' suffix is no longer necessary
* some other minor changes

Closes-Bug: 1376457
Change-Id: I72134bcdf6c42911d07e65952a9a56331d896699

commit_message:
Implement the Conductor side of ring rebalancing

Adds an RPC fanout-cast to notify all conductor instances that the hash
ring distribution has changed. This causes each conductor to update its
local caches as appropriate by calling prepare() or cleanup() on
existing deployments, and starting or stopping console sessions.

Co-Authored-By: Michael Davies <michael@the-davies.net>

Change-Id: Ifb3d837b40519a93cfed850b066cfb89e923fbdb

commit_message:
image: make sure created_images attribute exists on resource_cleanup

If the test is skipped before created_images is initialized we'll trace
on resource_cleanup, so make sure the attribute is set before trying to
use it.

Closes-Bug: #1375475

Change-Id: I1908bb9fc4bdf98801d4903cd0ddf4eb664feb63

[{'created': '2014-09-29 20:51:41.000000000', 'message': "Check for class attributes on resource_cleanup in case of skipException

If a sub-class overrides resource_setup and raises a skipException
before the class attributes used in resource_cleanup are initialized
we'll hit AttributeErrors, so make sure the attributes are set before
trying to use them in resource_cleanup calls.

Closes-Bug: #1375461

Change-Id: I1e1474622f47f4171b78ca71dde1b4411951c82f
"}, {'created': '2014-09-29 21:08:31.000000000', 'message': 'compute: check for class attributes on resource_cleanup

If a skipException is raised from resource_setup before
attributes are set which are used in resource_cleanup,
we get AttributeError traces in the tempest log.

This handles the current traces seen in the compute API
tests.

Closes-Bug: #1375461

Change-Id: I1e1474622f47f4171b78ca71dde1b4411951c82f
'}]
commit_message:
compute: check for class attributes on resource_cleanup

If a skipException is raised from resource_setup before
attributes are set which are used in resource_cleanup,
we get AttributeError traces in the tempest log.

This handles the current traces seen in the compute API
tests.

Closes-Bug: #1375461

Change-Id: I1e1474622f47f4171b78ca71dde1b4411951c82f

commit_message:
orchestration: check for attributes in resource_cleanup

If the test is skipped the attributes in resource_setup might not be
initialized so we'll trace with AttributeErrors in resource_cleanup, so
check for those attributes before using them in resource_cleanup.

Part of blueprint resource-cleanup

Change-Id: Ic3c5f32fe04ddc5504d9a9f2a74a9894b6e67ca8

[{'created': '2014-10-02 06:29:53.000000000', 'message': "Fix tests comparing tokens

There were tests that verified that the PKI token body could be
encrypted with CMS and compared to the token ID in the response.
This test isn't safe because the token body may be different than
the token encrypted with CMS since the order of items in the dict
can change.

The fix is to change the test to decode the PKI token ID and
compare that to the response body JSON instead.

Conflicts:
	keystone/tests/test_v3_auth.py

Change-Id: Icc649b96071ff084d5c76f2ea2bcf3ecb08a0351
"}]
commit_message:
Fix tests comparing tokens

There were tests that verified that the PKI token body could be
encrypted with CMS and compared to the token ID in the response.
This test isn't safe because the token body may be different than
the token encrypted with CMS since the order of items in the dict
can change.

The fix is to change the test to decode the PKI token ID and
compare that to the response body JSON instead.

Conflicts:
	keystone/tests/test_v3_auth.py

Change-Id: Icc649b96071ff084d5c76f2ea2bcf3ecb08a0351

Commit 867bdedf81533f283aae4de4488d54c254bb7f07 added a test that raises
an exception using the libvirt VIR_ERR_CONFIG_UNSUPPORTED error code but
missed adding that to fakelibvirt, so the test won't work if you don't

commit_message:
Add VIR_ERR_CONFIG_UNSUPPORTED to fakelibvirt

Commit 867bdedf81533f283aae4de4488d54c254bb7f07 added a test that raises
an exception using the libvirt VIR_ERR_CONFIG_UNSUPPORTED error code but
missed adding that to fakelibvirt, so the test won't work if you don't
have libvirt installed.

This simply adds the constant to fakelibvirt.

Closes-Bug: #1376363

Change-Id: I909608a7f1a8b5ee407b1d01896bc9db1adcee4e

commit_message:
Remove unused elevated context param from quota helper methods

The elevated context being passed to the _quota_usage_create and
_reservation_create methods is not used, so remove it from the formal
parameter list of those methods and related usage.

This is part of a larger series to refactor the quota_reserve method.

Partial-Bug: #1369605

Change-Id: I50749402177eda29ae006ec4fd11a9a8125765ec

commit_message:
Remove xmlutils module

The xmlutils module is being removed from oslo-incubator as it's not
useful anymore. Various fixes have been integrated into the base XML
module provided by Python now.

See
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/047368.html
for details.

Change-Id: Iefa1a5a4d08a3cfc43b3c9764fc2d35c328a19e3

commit_message:
Remove Nova v3 API test configuration

Nova v3 API has disappeared in Juno cycle, and we don't test the API
now on the gate since If63dcdb2d05aa0fab0b6848a1248b6678f1ee9ad .
This patch removes Nova v3 API test configuration.

Change-Id: Ie2e10d603e10b0f05ec7767ea41b5fe9aca84ccc

commit_message:
Add unit test for cache-url

A sanity check that cache-url does the right thing when presented
with the appropriate curl return codes.  This change brings in the
test code for scripts from tripleo-image-elements, which needs to
be factored out into a place both projects can use it.

I'm stubbing out curl so we don't have a dep on curl in our unit
tests, and because I've seen some strange behavior out of curl in
the gate that caused random failures in this test.

Change-Id: I31e6b06b45415feec7285511d07e65eb78d0d045

commit_message:
Enable DVR + HA support

Juno brings two new big features:
- distributed routers
- router high availability

This patchs aims to allow the users to configure DVR and/or HA routers.
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Change-Id: Iaab5ab7e63f2627381ca1d5bb1cfd836433d734e

commit_message:
Improve the Installation Guide: Compute agent for Telemetry section

1. Restructured content
2. Removed openstack-config commands
3. Replaced auth_host, auth_port and auth_protocol keys with identity_uri and auth_uri keys

Partial-bug: 1301034
Change-Id: Ifdc6068b5042811df3cb008b7e0a8f9c7ba4c51e
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements

Restart container until mariadb is available

Fix a race condition between MariaDB service start and Keystone.

commit_message:
Normalize Gerrit ACLs

This is the result of running:

    find gerrit/acls/ -type f -name "*.config" \
        -exec ./tools/normalize_acl.py {} 1 2 3 4 5 6 \;

Change-Id: Icc447d5c413008138c88daba6fe8e1bd72bfe65e

[{'created': '2014-09-17 05:45:52.000000000', 'message': 'Always set DATA_DIR

I noticed this when debugging [1]

devstack is intended to set $DATA_DIR to $DEST/data by default, but
currently it does that *before* reading localrc so it always uses its
default $DEST value of /opt/stack.

The code in devstack-gate.sh directly chowns /opt/stack/data/tempest
for the tempest user; this is required for tempest to be able to write
out lock-files.  This currently works due to the above, but if
devstack is fixed to correctly locate DATA_DIR under DEST, the chowned
path is now wrong.

The issue is made more confusing as the extant code explicitly sets
DATA_DIR if running grenade (why is not really explained in the
original change [2]).

The solution is to always explicitly set DATA_DIR to $BASE/data.
Since this is /opt/stack/data, the existing devstack (which
essentially assumes this path) continues to work.  A fixed devstack
will use the explicitly set path and continue to work.

There is no need to explicitly set SWIFT_DATA_DIR as that appears to
be a work-around for an old bug [3]

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/120085/

commit_message:
Always set DATA_DIR

I noticed this when debugging [1]

devstack is intended to set $DATA_DIR to $DEST/data by default, but
currently it does that *before* reading localrc so it always uses its
default $DEST value of /opt/stack.

The code in devstack-gate.sh directly chowns /opt/stack/data/tempest
for the tempest user; this is required for tempest to be able to write
out lock-files.  This currently works due to the above, but if
devstack is fixed to correctly locate DATA_DIR under DEST, the chowned
path is now wrong.

The issue is made more confusing as the extant code explicitly sets
DATA_DIR if running grenade (why is not really explained in the
original change [2]).

The solution is to always explicitly set DATA_DIR to $BASE/data.
Since this is /opt/stack/data, the existing devstack (which
essentially assumes this path) continues to work.  A fixed devstack
will use the explicitly set path and continue to work.

There is no need to explicitly set SWIFT_DATA_DIR as that appears to
be a work-around for an old bug [3]

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/120085/
[2] Id3e7e6d7b44fb715db3bb15600473f776bc87440
[3] https://bugs.launchpad.net/devstack/+bug/1162303

Change-Id: Ic8948bbed51dd90e6c350785a47d539efd589e64

commit_message:
Deprecate / obsolete NetApp volume extra specs

The NetApp Data ONTAP (Cluster-mode) NFS & iSCSI drivers for Juno support
the Cinder pools feature, but the drivers are reporting two qualified
extra specs that must be converted to unqualified extra specs in order to
be used by the Cinder scheduler's capability filter. Furthermore, there
are four extra specs that must be deprecated due to having the pools
feature.  Warnings will be logged during volume creation if any of the
obsolete or deprecated extra specs are seen in the volume type.

Change-Id: I4dbd667610e481356304a12b8dae84cff61aa9d9
Closes-bug: 1374630

commit_message:
Sync SQLAlchemy lifecycle to request cycle

SQLAlchemy session/transaction lifecycles should be synchronized to
request lifecycles, initiating with session binding to the database
engine, followed by data model processing, followed by either a
commit() or rollback(), and finally a session disposal once the request
is completed. This CR creates repository module functions for each of
these lifecycle operations. For the API process, this means utilizing
Pecan's transaction hook to invoke the SQLAlchemy lifecycle functions
above. For the Worker process, this means decorating each RPC method
invoked from queue to call the above lifecycle functions.

Change-Id: Id7216eb6871dae849f782a0f196210cd85d08f2f
Closes-Bug: #1376239

commit_message:
add the src lib forward testing to all of oslo

This gives all the oslo projects a job where they test their current
git against a devstack where all the rest of the libraries are at
release versions, but the server projects are at current head. It lets
an oslo library ensure that it's not going to ruin the world when it
releases.

Change-Id: I674dfa571d11ab810a3e6ba8146fbc75ea5da6f2

There were tests that verified that the PKI token body could be
encrypted with CMS and compared to the token ID in the response.
This test isn't safe because the token body may be different than
the token encrypted with CMS since the order of items in the dict
can change.

commit_message:
Fix tests comparing tokens

There were tests that verified that the PKI token body could be
encrypted with CMS and compared to the token ID in the response.
This test isn't safe because the token body may be different than
the token encrypted with CMS since the order of items in the dict
can change.

The fix is to change the test to decode the PKI token ID and
compare that to the response body JSON instead.

Change-Id: Icc649b96071ff084d5c76f2ea2bcf3ecb08a0351

Currently glance_store is running all the jobs that glance runs. I think
these jobs are way more than what we need to test the library and they
may be wasting some resources in the gate. The patch proposes to run

Change-Id: Ib8525629277803473e5c7d9fdd402d1738b3b2e3

commit_message:
Don't run neutron/heat jobs for glance_store

Currently glance_store is running all the jobs that glance runs. I think
these jobs are way more than what we need to test the library and they
may be wasting some resources in the gate. The patch proposes to run
just tempest and full jobs, which removes large-ops, heat and neutron
jobs.

Change-Id: Ib8525629277803473e5c7d9fdd402d1738b3b2e3

commit_message:
VMware: Remove class orphaned by ESX driver removal

HostState was only used by the ESX driver, which was removed in
change I718fc0ee67dbd625af00c20fa4e34b8a35015437.

Also remove LOG, which is no longer used following previous removals.

Change-Id: I22e30c01e5b5219df858219dc1fda335a83ad225

commit_message:
VMware: Remove VMwareImage.file_size_in_gb

file_size_in_gb was rounding down. This is counter intuitive, as a
512MB disk is reported as 0GB. However, this rounding weirdness was
required for correctness in a way which wasn't obvious. When we test
if an image needs to be resized, we test instance.root_gb >
image.file_size_in_gb. Because file_size_in_gb was rounded down, an
image slightly smaller than 1GB will be reported as 0GB and therefore
resized.

The source of the rounding confusion is the bytes->gb conversion. To
make the code more obviously correct, I have switched it to instead
convert gb->bytes, which does not involve rounding. To ensure this
never trips anybody up, I have removed file_size_in_gb.

Change-Id: I99d20e3b1383e29cddff3d1016c4bcedc1683c4d

commit_message:
Remove the nova-manage flavor sub-command

The nova-manage flavor sub-command was deprecated in Juno milestone-1
via commit a601556684f18059e478ba645aff8276c9c78a4a with a note that it
will be removed in Kilo.

This removes it.

Change I4e2399f2fbab2c20299dd62c104b9220c1d36fb2 is to remove the
related Tempest tests.

Change-Id: I1798c8a0697009b3dcebeb818580c8323880e395

commit_message:
Added jobs for MongoDB and Percona datastores

Reasons:
 - for provisioning Trove instance we've used publisher to push images to tarball.o.o,
   but we(Trove devs) did this only for MySQL datastore.
   It is time to go forward and add another tested datastores, such as:
   - percona
   - mongodb

Change-Id: I44c7e113e6a51ff61683c57f82287b84fc38f27b

commit_message:
Support Nova availability zones

Extend API to support Nova availability zone selection for node groups
and node group templates.  This patch modifies the two provisioning
engines (direct and Heat) and includes changes to the DB schema.

DocImpact

Implements: blueprint support-nova-availability-zones
Change-Id: Id03848fd8d5949fa5ecbc494639fe59a70ddced3

The string passed to ldap.str2dn() needs to be UTF8 encoded, otherwise
we encounter UnicodeEncodeError exceptions.

This patch adds UTF8 encoding where it was missing for ldap.str2dn()
calls as well as some unit tests to cover the functions that were
lacking this encoding step.

Change-Id: I96e718f1d43f4aad272ca4990d3905a5adf1f07d

'}]
commit_message:
Convert unicode to UTF8 when calling ldap.str2dn()

The string passed to ldap.str2dn() needs to be UTF8 encoded, otherwise
we encounter UnicodeEncodeError exceptions.

This patch adds UTF8 encoding where it was missing for ldap.str2dn()
calls as well as some unit tests to cover the functions that were
lacking this encoding step.

Change-Id: I96e718f1d43f4aad272ca4990d3905a5adf1f07d
Closes-bug: #1375139
(cherry picked from commit 09d38008aa0e7f8c6802088c807dd0ad6ba80e10)

commit_message:
Fix parsing of emulated enabled DN

If a non-default emulated enabled DN is specified in configuration,
the DN structure returned from python-ldap is incorrectly converted
to a string.  This leads to an index error when we attempt to extract
the RDN attribute and value.

This patch removes the incorrect string conversion and instead does
the proper conversion on the RDN strings that we extract.

Change-Id: I8f0c4594cfa9a41e1875870c3eb63fae32c8c041
Resolves-bug: #1375772
(cherry picked from commit 5380ddaadb0ce34b866b097cb6ac1396d2b30100)

[{'created': '2014-10-01 03:04:20.000000000', 'message': "Handle default string values when using user_enabled_invert

When the user_enabled_invert setting is being used, values returned
from LDAP are ultimately converted to a bool type when we reach the
inversion logic.  If the user_enabled_default value is used due to
no value being returned from LDAP, the type is a string.  This causes
the inversion logic to be evaluated incorrectly, as 'not' will return
False for any non-empty string.  This results in disabled accounts
that should be enabled.

Change-Id: Id7b024c12815748305458ca05fc8f8a6324c1908
Closes-bug: #1376053
(cherry picked from commit 50a6312ffa1f636bd74c98d9938ea4083bed2768)
"}]
commit_message:
Handle default string values when using user_enabled_invert

When the user_enabled_invert setting is being used, values returned
from LDAP are ultimately converted to a bool type when we reach the
inversion logic.  If the user_enabled_default value is used due to
no value being returned from LDAP, the type is a string.  This causes
the inversion logic to be evaluated incorrectly, as 'not' will return
False for any non-empty string.  This results in disabled accounts
that should be enabled.

Change-Id: Id7b024c12815748305458ca05fc8f8a6324c1908
Closes-bug: #1376053
(cherry picked from commit 50a6312ffa1f636bd74c98d9938ea4083bed2768)

commit_message:
debian: do not enable grizzly repository from gplhost

There is not reason to enable this additional repository anymore.
All the important packages are either in wheezy or wheezy-backports.

Change-Id: I47af16ba6b507fc929b0d2948c757f4060ba93a5
(cherry picked from commit 5420992a2cad4c0a23e436f5f416011f46c97ecd)

commit_message:
Update hackings jobs

* Make pypy voting again. It was disabled due to some issues, but
  it appears to be working again.
* Drop gate-hacking-integration-nova from gate, as the job is designed
  to be non-voting.
* Add python34 job as non-voting, as the first step in getting python34
  support.

Change-Id: Icaf5848eec8b30d77f4c5a8a21f7e6ca4ccc7924

commit_message:
Allow access to nova-docker stable branches

Enable gerrit review for nova-docker stable branches.
We'll be adding a stable/icehouse branch immediately
and a stable/juno branch, once released.

Change-Id: I28c1d4a6758d36709d6a86d6ca25ca5682f4113b

[{'created': '2014-10-01 17:50:05.000000000', 'message': 'Fix local bashate runs

My repository contained .test directory from different tests and
that failed the bashate test, exclude it from bashate checks so
that tox -e bashate works locally.

Change-Id: I99c531d425cfc4464ec7461b339fd0b40ce13148
'}]
commit_message:
Fix local bashate runs

My repository contained .test directory from different tests and
that failed the bashate test, exclude it from bashate checks so
that tox -e bashate works locally.

Change-Id: I99c531d425cfc4464ec7461b339fd0b40ce13148

commit_message:
Ensure process_router_floating_ips runs correctly

When removing a router with an external floating IP, the port
removal takes place first, and then the router removal process
fails because the floating IP cannot be removed successfully
now that the port is missing.  Checking only ex_gw_port seems
to solve the issue.

bug #1203782

Change-Id: Id5f69b99a7501922efcc97460c3e4b384d82e353

[{'created': '2014-10-01 09:19:10.000000000', 'message': 'Cleanup _convert_block_devices

_convert_block_devices was instantiating 2 objects for every 1
returned due to the _is_transformable test. This change simplifies the
code by removing the nested function, and at the same time does the
conversion in a single pass, which is more efficient.

Change-Id: Id6b583a1c08d684fcff073dd0289be8e3919ba0a
'}]
commit_message:
Cleanup _convert_block_devices

_convert_block_devices was instantiating 2 objects for every 1
returned due to the _is_transformable test. This change simplifies the
code by removing the nested function, and at the same time does the
conversion in a single pass, which is more efficient.

Change-Id: Id6b583a1c08d684fcff073dd0289be8e3919ba0a

commit_message:
Remove dependencies from docs test env in tox.ini

Because the docs environment inherits from the greater 'testenv', which
has the dependencies already mentioned, there is no need to
have them listed again for the 'docs' environment.

Change-Id: I83830e47b44cab2a9d44a67827f3f28b687c5fdd

commit_message:
Open Kilo development

Bump pre-version to 2015.1 to formally open master branch to Kilo
development.

Change-Id: Ia48ad29dc1b31b1fbcb14dfffad571659ec66700

Removing my +1.  Talked to John Griffith about this as the issue sounded familiar.  He had the following to share:

<jungleboyj> jgriffith: Why does this issue sound familiar?  https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1374931
* bruff1 (~bruff@inet-rmmc06-o.oracle.com) has joined #openstack-cinder
<jgriffith> jungleboyj: yeah... we had discussions on this at one point
<jgriffith> jungleboyj: so the image in glance is "nothing", the actual snapshot in this case is a volume snapshot
<jungleboyj> jgriffith: I thought so.  This is one of those where the wrong info is being used for the size or something?
<jgriffith> the entry in Glance I *thought* pointed to it though

So, not allowing the image to be used may not be the right solution.'}, {'account_id': 9981, 'date': '2014-10-01 21:16:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Jay - thanks for asking about this.  It was vaguely in the back of my mind too.  

To restate what you are saying + mix it with my understanding: the size parameter in glance represents how much space an object is taking in glance.  Since volume snapshots aren't stored in glance they are properly (by their definition) represented as a 0 size item.

I think this patch is going to prevent every volume snapshot from launching."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-01 21:22:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

If an image snapshot should ever have a zero size, attempting to launch
a new image from it will lead to errors in the browser, which in turn
causes horizon to appear to be broken.  Prevent getting into that
situation by only permitting the launch action when the size is greater
than zero.

Closes-Bug: 1374931
Change-Id: Ied0eb41f5198d935bbb0896e5004ea78176bc2b8

commit_message:
Enable launching instance from zero-size image snapshot

Remove the general hardcoded minimum of 1GB volume size on the create
instance workflow, and selectively enforce it when the volume size field
is used and editable: namely, when launching an instance from an image
and creating a new volume.

This general minimum was preventing the launch of instances from image
snapshots (whose size is reported as 0) by causing browser errors as the
browser tried to highlight the error of the invisible size field.

Closes-Bug: 1374931
Change-Id: Ied0eb41f5198d935bbb0896e5004ea78176bc2b8

commit_message:
Explicitly depend on six in requirements file

Six is used directly in oslo.db (and is not just a transitive
dependency) so it should be listed in the requirements file
just like other non-transitive dependencies.

Change-Id: I81d2d7d0db9142bace7ecf8882efbbcd605fb527

commit_message:
Skip aggregates tests to match Public Cloud

Skip aggregates tests to match the skipping of those tests in Public Cloud
due to conflicts with HPCS. Those tests also currently prevent the landing
of the change: I160bac193dd3c2659453e0a97466996bffc2af8f (JIRA: NOVA-669)
in HP Helion CE. This last change requires deeper investigation.

Change-Id: Ia8c94b1deafe7858d9af0619a7e20ea7ad9c6521

commit_message:
Refuse invalid qcow2 backing files

Don't allow qcow2 files that are pointing to backing files outside of:

volume-<id>
volume-<id>.<snap-id>
volume-<id>.tmp-snap-<snap-id>

(optionally prefixed with /mnt/path)

Closes-Bug: #1350504

Change-Id: I2a277920f64dd4ede3b988beefee595585d8fdac

check and gate queue.

commit_message:
specify node type correctly for new -src jobs

I did not specify node type, which made this a bare node job, but it
really needs to be a devstack node job.

Also remove redundant check job definition, we'll just use gate- for
check and gate queue.

Change-Id: Ib71e365ed497f7db2aeded9e4628ef20da604392

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-02 19:58:45.000000000', 'message': 'Skip orchestration tests if Neutron is not available

Both scenario.orchestration.test_autoscaling and
scenario.orchestration.test_server_cfn_init fail if Neutron is not
available. Neutron is not currently configured with default DevsStack,
so running default set of tests after using DevStack would fail.

This patch would skip both of the tests when Neutron is not available.

Better solution would probably involve using nova network when
neutron is not configured.

Change-Id: Ic047e131267026c2986da174ea05205f4145434a
Closes-bug: #1333875
'}, {'created': '2014-09-04 16:22:03.000000000', 'message': "Skip orchestration tests if Neutron is not available

Both scenario.orchestration.test_autoscaling and
scenario.orchestration.test_server_cfn_init fail if Neutron is not
available. Neutron is not currently configured with default DevsStack,
so running default set of tests after using DevStack would fail.

This patch adds 'neutron' service tag to these tests, which would skip
them if Neutron is not available.

Change-Id: Ic047e131267026c2986da174ea05205f4145434a
Closes-bug: #1333875

commit_message:
Skip orchestration test if Neutron is not available

scenario.orchestration.test_server_cfn_init fails if Neutron is not
available. Neutron is not currently configured by default DevStack,
so running default set of tests after using DevStack would fail.

This patch would skip the test by using explicit no-Neutron skip.
It also adds 'network' service dependency to the list of service tags.
Note that the 'network' service tag never skips a test, as it is
assumed that nova-network is always available. This is why we need
and explicit skip.

Another solution that was considered is adding a new 'neutron'
service tag that would be used until nova-network deprecation is
complete. The argument against it is that having both 'network' and
'neutron' tags would cause confusion.

Closes-bug: #1333875
Change-Id: Ic047e131267026c2986da174ea05205f4145434a

commit_message:
Unwrap DialectFunctionDispatcher from itself.

The DialectFunctionDispatcher.dispatch_for() decorator method
necessarily returns the dispatcher itself and not the
decorated function, so that the object can continue to be
re-used even if the function name is the same as that of the
dispatcher.   In order to support a single function being
wrapped by the dispatcher multiple times with different
criteria, dispatch_for() will now check for the last function
wrapped and use that.

Change-Id: I331670d9b76ae30e7a666648e7e2d4c72641c9ff
Closes-Bug: #1373568

commit_message:
Update tearDown methods in API integration tests

After testing new script run_functional_tests one destructive issue
was discovered that after this script all executions were deleted.

This situation was fixed. Now in all create methods identifier of
created object saves in array and in tearDown methods tests delete
only objects which were saved in appropriate arrays.

Change-Id: I442aecd346c003cd38ce6977e4f69f9bfa32e894

commit_message:
Fix instance cross AZ check when attaching volumes

For CONF.cinder_cross_az_attach=False, we currently only check the desired AZ
during scheduling but don't actually check the final AZ of the node.

When attaching volumes to running instances we need to check the actual
AZ on the instance and not the desired AZ at boot time. The desired AZ
attribute is optional at boot and may not be set or the desired AZ
could be different from the final AZ.
When we are booting with a volume however we don't know the final AZ so we
check on the desired AZ.

Closes-Bug: #1255347
Change-Id: Ied912c171100a450754d315027bf5c407ac067bb

commit_message:
Create a nested helper function that will work on py3.x

The contextlib.nested function doesn't exist on py3.x so
in order to retain similar functionality create an equivalent
that will perform good enough for oslo.db usage.

Change-Id: I326816c9301f1c625e1e2723d4d639fd81cc596c

commit_message:
Start adding a environment for py34/py33

Get a tox environment for py34/py33 that doesn't stop the existing
py26 and py27 to continue working with the adjusted test-requirements since
MySQL-python and sqlalchemy-migrate do not yet exist in 3.x.

Note that this does not fully make py34 work yet but it starts to work
in this direction of getting it to work (which will apparently require
quite a big more tweaking).

Change-Id: I024957a76f2de0bd406d14da5af6e4caf3d493e7

commit_message:
ceilometer compute agent not started correctly

command isn't properly parsed after switch to run_process. this
patch corrects the regression

Change-Id: Ib28d4bbf6f150854fc5aa04e3fa4eed92005ce19
Closes-Bug: #1370673
(cherry picked from commit bdeea69d726eca7a899b1d2225d213724b31df22)

commit_message:
Use six.wraps instead of functools.wraps

The six module provides a helper wraps function that correctly
tracks the original wrapped function in python 2.x and 3.x so
use it where we can so that we maintain better compatability with
3.x

Change-Id: Ifa994bf63153f58f0aa1f6203a963ac7312ac2b1

commit_message:
Use the six provided iterator mix-in

Instead of having a customized next() and __next__() methods
just use the mix-in that six provides and used it to avoid
having to declare our own next() compatability function.

Change-Id: I1a5fc9bd43783577af879476ca46afcc668185f5

commit_message:
Fixing iSER transport protocol for LVMISERDriver

ISER capabilities were broken in icehouse when trying to remove
duplication between ISCSIDriver and ISERDriver.

This fix does minimal changes in the code in order to fix
the capability.

The fix is basically re-adding the ISERTgtAdm and re-adding
the support in LVMISERDriver: change target_lun based on
iseradm.

Closes-Bug: #1336648
Change-Id: Icd907d5b2aa4415f8ff1972d64b27a787f3fc7a9
Signed-off-by: Aviram Bar-Haim <aviramb@mellanox.com>
(cherry picked from commit 1a7af74d2ff5e2ba32d6f0aff71bc8789ed8e317)
